nt wipes or polishes it with a red cloth, treating even the nozzle as something to be cleaned carefully. Through the car window, a woman inside watches him, her face partially framed by the dark interior and the window opening.\n\nFrom inside the car looking outward, the attendant stands outside the window in front of the station building. He poses with one hand on his hip and the other arm raised, as if presenting his completed service for judgment. Inside the dark, limousine-like passenger compartment sit several formally dressed adults in suits, including a woman and older men. They hold up large white scorecards with bold black numbers. Cards marked “10,” “9,” and “6” are raised and shuffled into view above their laps and near the roof opening.\n\nThe front of the silver sedan is shown with scorecards protruding above the roofline. At first the visible scores include “10” and “6,” then the judges’ cards change until three “10” cards are displayed across the top of the car. Another card marked “9” appears at the side. The car’s chrome grille and hood ornament remain centered below the cards, reinforcing the judging theme.\n\nThe final image becomes more graphic and stylized. The silver car remains at the center while the scorecards hover above it, reading “10 10 10 9.” Pale, sweeping shapes pass around the vehicle like animated panels or a visual wipe. The Shell pecten logo appears large and centered over the car’s windshield and grille. Across the lower left and bottom of the image, bold white text comes into view reading “The Move Is On,” paired with the Shell logo as the commercial’s closing visual.",
